Pretty on the Inside 1991



Pretty on the Inside is the debut studio album by American alternative rock group Hole, released in September 1991 on Caroline Records. Featuring dramatic, experimental, and abrasive music and vocals that are whispered, spoken, and shouted, the album contains lyrics that emphasize alienation, feminism, and self-hatred. Pretty on the Inside was Hole's first full-length album, and their only release on Caroline Records.

The recording of the album took place over the course of four days, and resulted in two newly-written songs (&quot;Starbelly&quot; and &quot;Sassy&quot;) as well as recordings of songs that had never been or rarely had been played live (&quot;Loaded&quot; and &quot;Good Sister/Bad Sister&quot;). The album was very well-received at the time of its release, but was quickly eclipsed both critically and on the music charts when Nirvana's Nevermind was released, and yet again when Hole released their second album, Live Through This, which featured a more streamlined sound.

Pretty on the Inside had a wide-ranging influence on the underground music scene of the 1990s, being specifically mentioned by, among others, Distillers frontwoman Brody Dalle in an interview as a seminal album in the development of her music


